            <p>As anyone who has every made the mistake of accepting an invitation to Thanksgiving dinner at my house will attest, I am not a good pie maker. This is in part due to a lack of trying. I generally only bake one or two pies each year and I make them for Thanksgiving. My wife, a very skilled former professional chef, has no interest in baking pies, so despite my lack of talent, it falls to me to uphold the grand tradition of Thanksgiving pie making. I make my own crust, which generally requires a well-swung cleaver to cut, and fill the cement-like creation with whatever kooky, experimental recipe was featured in the <em>New York Times</em> in the run-up to the holiday. No one ever asks to take a slice home with them.</p>

            <p>So nothing about my early morning, early November adventure in pie making was expected or, perhaps, welcomed, but I was obsessed. It started with a simple fact. Suwan Aryal and I have assembled a database of recipes extracted from the over 100 Mississippi community cookbooks published before 1970 digitized by The University of Southern Mississippi. The data shows that the most common recipe is for pecan pie. As such, pecan pie seemed like a topic worth investigating, although most of my historical food writing to date has focused on the lives of those who make and eat food, rather than specific recipes. To my surprise, the story of pecan pie turned out to be more akin to a Dan Brown novel than a Mark Bittman cookbook.</p>

            <p>The twisted tale of the pecan pie would also, also unexpectedly, reaffirm what I have come to understand about American cooking in the twentieth century while working on book about community cookbooks. It is a story of homemakers and innovation, the shifting meanings we attach to food, and the development of a national cuisine.</p>

            <hr style="border: 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); margin: 2rem 0;">

            <p>Pecan trees are native to Mississippi (as well as other states in the Mississippi River Valley and Texas), but it was not until the late nineteenth century that new cultivation techniques produced consistent, large, and easily shelled nuts.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-3" id="pp1-ref-3" class="footnote-ref">3</a></sup> One of the most successful of these new trees produced “paper shell” pecans and was bred, nursed, and sold commercially by Colonel William R. Stuart of Ocean Springs in Jackson County, Mississippi. The Stuart Pecan Company successfully marketed both its trees and its nuts at events like the 1893 Columbian Exposition, and was soon supplying trees throughout the South.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-4" id="pp1-ref-4" class="footnote-ref">4</a></sup> Rival nurseries sprang up in Jackson County and by 1920 there were thirty-two nurseries—the largest which “contained more than 13,000 young pecan trees”—and new competitors in states across the South.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-5" id="pp1-ref-5" class="footnote-ref">5</a></sup> Encouraged by agricultural scientists eager to find ways to diversify Southern crops, farmers planted pecan orchards from Georgia to Texas.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-6" id="pp1-ref-6" class="footnote-ref">6</a></sup></p>

            <p>The boom in pecan production was as much a real estate boondoggle as an agricultural revolution. Following the well-tread path of speculators who sold satsuma and tung oil orchards, investors seized upon the opportunities the newly cultivated trees presented. As food historian Andrew Smith writes:</p>

            <div class="professor-voice">
              <p>At the time, the cotton crop in the South was devastated by the boll weevil, and property values had collapsed. Northern companies purchased vast acreage in the South, planted paper shell pecans, and sold sections of the plantings as investments. One company that excelled at this was the Oak Ridge Pecan Company, based near Chicago. It purchased land in Florida and then sold it at a substantial profit. . . . Another Chicago-based land scheme was the Mobile Farm Land Company, which sold paper shell pecan acreage around Mobile, Alabama. It offered an Assured Income for Life and a Home for Retirement Adjoining a City of 75,000 People on the Gulf Coast.</p>
              <br>
              <p>Yet another company that engaged in land speculation was headed by Elam G. Hess, the president of the Keystone Pecan Company in Manheim, Pennsylvania. It was formed in 1912, when he acquired 10,500 acres of land near Albany, Georgia, and planted 20 trees to the acre, for a total of 210,000 trees.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-7" id="pp1-ref-7" class="footnote-ref">7</a></sup></p>
            </div>

            <p>As more acreage was planted, the ready availability of inexpensive pecans increased and pecan consumption rose, but the success of the new industry was not guaranteed. As historian James McWilliams writes, “With supply as high as it was, producers would have to rely on the culinary creativity of American cooks and consumers to persuade Americans to eat pecans as a staple product.”<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-8" id="pp1-ref-8" class="footnote-ref">8</a></sup> Not all of the early uses succeeded. While health food advocates, especially vegetarians such as Dr. John Harvey Kellogg, promoted nuts as an alternative to meat, efforts to market these health products often failed. Kellogg sold pecan butter as an alternative to peanut butter, for example, but few liked the taste. Similarly, hopes that pecans might produce a cooking oil also amounted to nothing.</p>

            <p>By the turn of the century, Andrew Smith writes, “about 75 percent of the commercial pecans were sold as salted nut meats—whole kernels in one piece, halves, or pieces—and were supplied to restaurants and hotels and for home consumption.”<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-9" id="pp1-ref-9" class="footnote-ref">9</a></sup> Most of these pecans were eaten as loose nuts, although some found their way into salads and turkey stuffing and some candies.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-10" id="pp1-ref-10" class="footnote-ref">10</a></sup> Though a popular recipe for pecan cake circulated at the turn of the century and Fannie Farmer advocated for pecan brownies in her 1896 cookbook, pecan recipes rarely seemed to capture the nation’s culinary imagination. Pecan consumption was second only to walnuts, and they were particularly popular in the South, but despite the federal government’s promotion of nuts as a meat alternative during voluntary rationing during World War I, the market was not growing as fast as the rapidly maturing pecans orchards could produce nuts.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-11" id="pp1-ref-11" class="footnote-ref">11</a></sup></p>

            <p>There was one success story, pralines. Originally called “plarines,” the sugary candies were sold by Black women street vendors in New Orleans. The candies were the marriage of native pecans gleaned from trees around the city and low-quality sugar produced in the cane fields around New Orleans. Since the Civil War, at least, they were created and sold by Black entrepreneurs who hawked them as a cheap, high-calorie snack for freed Black labors and later as a sweet treat for New Orleanians. When the availability of inexpensive, cultivated pecans increased in the late nineteenth century, white candy manufacturers seized the opportunity to cater to the increasingly lucrative tourist trade. They rebranded the Africa-inspired candy, fabricated a history that traced the origins of the praline (and its name) to French royalty, and systematically drove Black women from the marketplace. Visitors to New Orleans loved the pecan candies and soon recipes were appearing in newspaper columns and cookbooks. As Anthony Stanosis writes in his recent book on the invention of the New Orleans praline tradition, “by the 1920s, the term ‘pralines’ had become synonymous in the United States with the use of pecans.”<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-12" id="pp1-ref-12" class="footnote-ref">12</a></sup></p>

