            <p>Pralines’ success in New Orleans led to some of the earliest recipes for pecans in our database. <em>The Laurel Cook Book</em>, originally published in 1900, includes a recipe for New Orleans Pecan Pralines.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-13" id="pp1-ref-13" class="footnote-ref">13</a></sup> Likewise, <em>Tried and True</em> from Gulfport, Mississippi, published in 1906 includes a recipe for “Nut Candies” that allows for the use of pecans or walnuts. The cookbook also includes a recipe for “Candies” that, in addition to the standard praline ingredients, features a small amount of chocolate. Both these cookbooks are from southern Mississippi and both communities had strong connections to New Orleans.</p>

            <p>If the pecan industry was to thrive, however, it would need more than pralines. Low prices encouraged both pecan growers seeking to increase demand and housewives eager to exploit the inexpensive nut to develop new recipes. The most successful of these new recipes—at least until Bordon’s introduction of pecan praline ice cream in the 1950s—was pecan pie.</p>

            <p>Pecan pie seems to have made its first appearance following the Civil War. Andrew Smith observes that the first “located” recipes appeared simultaneously in <em>Harper’s Bazaar</em> and <em>Texas Siftings</em> on February 6, 1886.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-14" id="pp1-ref-14" class="footnote-ref">14</a></sup> Other recipes soon followed in regional and national publications. These recipes plopped a handful of pecan pieces into or on top of a custard base and covered the whole with a meringue. The resulting pie was similar to a host of other contemporary pies, most notably chess pie (sometimes called transparent pie), whose first located recipes appeared in print twenty years before the first recipes for pecan pie.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-15" id="pp1-ref-15" class="footnote-ref">15</a></sup> Some of the recipes were simple, containing nothing more than cream, sugar, eggs, and pecans, but some also included flour, butter, and flavorings such as vanilla.</p>

            <p>Although custard pecan pie recipes began appearing in cookbooks, the dessert was not especially popular. Neither Fannie Farmer’s 1896 <em>Boston School of Cooking Cook Book</em> nor Sarah Rorer’s 1902 <em>New Cook Book</em> nor <em>Good Housekeeping’s</em> 1909 <em>Woman’s Home Cook Book</em>, three of the most popular cookbooks of the early twentieth century, included the recipe. <em>The Settlement Cook Book</em>, published in 1901, also ignored pecan pie. To be fair, none of these cookbooks included a large number of pie recipes. Pies had fallen out of fashion in the late nineteenth century, criticized by nutritionists as heavy and indigestible.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-16" id="pp1-ref-16" class="footnote-ref">16</a></sup> Mrs. Rorer, in particular, was a famed critic of pies, although she did publish one of the earliest recipes for pecan pie identified with a specific place in 1898. “Texas Pecan Pie,” a custard pie submitted by “M.G.,” was included in a rather long list of random recipes Rorer featured in her column in the <em>Ladies Home Journal</em>.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-17" id="pp1-ref-17" class="footnote-ref">17</a></sup> Reflecting the tepid reception the custard version of pecan pie enjoyed, our database contains only one pecan pie recipe prior to the late 1920s. It is called simply “Nut Pie.”<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-18" id="pp1-ref-18" class="footnote-ref">18</a></sup></p>

            <p>It will come as no surprise to those who love a slice of gooey, sugary pecan-laden pie that the nineteenth-century custard pie failed to become a holiday favorite. And it is the story of this pie’s failure and the rise of its much more popular corn-syrup successor that led me, in a rather roundabout way, to cajole my beleaguered spouse into helping me bake a pecan pie on a Sunday morning weeks before Thanksgiving. Like many a food historian before me, I had become obsessed with the twisted tale of the rise of what historian Rebecca Sharpless calls “pecan pie as we know it.”<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-19" id="pp1-ref-19" class="footnote-ref">19</a></sup></p>

            <p>For many years, the story of the invention of the modern pecan pie, like that of the praline, has been simple, straightforward, and fake. This fabricated history was created by the makers of Karo corn syrup, who claimed that the “mixture of corn syrup, sugar, eggs, vanilla and pecans baked in a pie shell” to produce “the now classic Pecan Pie . . . destined to become a world class favorite” was discovered in 1930 by the wife of a corporate sales executive. It is not entirely clear to me when the company first made this claim—it does not show up in advertisements I have examined through the 1960s—but the company continues to promote this story on their foodservice website (although they no longer include it on their retail site).<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-20" id="pp1-ref-20" class="footnote-ref">20</a></sup></p>

            <div class="chart-container">
              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/Floral.png" 
                   alt="Vicksburg Floral Club Cook Book (1928) - Early Corn Syrup Pecan Pie Recipe" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>A number of scholars, most notably Rebecca Sharpless, Rossi Anastopoulo, and Sarah Wassberg Johnson, have debunked this story. They have documented recipes for corn-syrup pecan pie, the “now classic Pecan Pie,” printed in cookbooks before 1930 when Karo claims the recipe was invented.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-21" id="pp1-ref-21" class="footnote-ref">21</a></sup> Our database of Mississippi community cookbooks includes evidence of this as well. The <em>Vicksburg Floral Club Cook Book</em> of 1928 has a recipe for corn-syrup pecan pie and the <em>Greenville Home Economist Cook Book</em> of 1930 has two. And there is also ample evidence that bakeries were making corn-syrup pecan pie prior to its alleged invention by a Karo employee’s wife. As Rebecca Sharpless writes, Karo was being used by commercial bakers in the Mississippi Delta in the 1920s.</p>

            <div class="professor-voice">
              <p>In Memphis in 1929, Vieh Bakeries sold “everyone’s favorite, Vieh’s Karo Pecan Pie, made of pure Karo Syrup, full of pecans” for thirty-three cents. Down the road in Clarksville, Mississippi, the Delta Baking Company offered its Large Karo Pecan Pie for forty cents. And over in Shreveport in 1930, Big Chain’s Balcony Cafeteria sold “Our Delicious Karo Pecan Pie” for ten cents a slice. So clearly PPAWKI [pecan pie as we know it] was a thing in the South by the late 1920s.<sup><a href="#pp1-footnote-22" id="pp1-ref-22" class="footnote-ref">22</a></sup></p>
            </div>

            <p>If the Karo story is a fiction and Karo did not invent the modern pecan pie, who did? Simple as the question is, and despite some considerable ink spilled by those looking for the holy grail of golden syrup, there is no easy answer. As writers of mystery novels might say, the “plot thickens,” and that seems an equally adapt way to describe the convoluted and controversial story of how our ancestors’ runny custard pie was abandoned and gooey, corn-syrup pecan pie assumed its identity. So, like a mystery novel, this first installment of our tale ends with a cliffhanger. (I promise part two will offer you an answer, and although it is neither simple nor definitive, it will explain why I made that pie.)</p>

