          <div class="essay-inner">
            <p>Let’s start with the known facts. Pretty much all the forensic analyses of the origins of the modern pecan pie agree that it was inspired by a number of previous recipes, including the custard pecan pie and other custard and syrup pies such as chess, sugar, and molasses pie (as well as fashionable variations such as Jeff Davis Pie, Tyler Pie, and plantation pie). Molasses pie, a New England favorite with a long history that may stretch back to England, is possibly the mother pie, but since the term molasses was used widely to describe various sugar syrups from maple to cane, it is difficult to trace the evolutions of these various pie histories and draw anything like a straight line from molasses to pecan pie. A probable intermediary step from molasses pie to pecan pie was, I should think, the plantation pie, a molasses pie that was included in some influential Southern cookbooks. Martha Pritchard Stanford’s <em>The Old and New Cook Book</em>, a New Orleans cookbook published in 1904 that received favorable press, featured a recipe for plantation pie that called for boiling sugar, molasses [in this case, probably cane syrup], and butter, cooling the mixture, adding eggs, lemons juice, and flour, pouring it into a crust, and baking.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-1" id="pp2-ref-1" class="footnote-ref">1</a></sup> Exactly what role plantation pie played in inspiring pecan pie is not clear, but there is little question, given that corn syrup is what made the modern pecan pie easy to make and phenomenally popular, that the availability of canned sugary syrups were critical to the modern pecan pie’s success. Exactly who invented the modern syrupy pecan pie, when it happened, and where it happened is, however, is a sticky mess of a mystery.</p>

            <p>One theory dates the first modern pecan pie to at least 1900 and was offered by Rebecca Sharpless in a blog post for UNC Press. Sharpless identified two recipes from the 1920s, discussed below, that use corn syrup, but her research led her to think that there must be a syrupy precursor to those recipes and her search for the progenitor led her to Slidell, Louisiana.</p>

            <div class="professor-voice">
              <p>Into the computer I went one more time, and I hit pay dirt with <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes Used in the South for More than 200 Years</em>, a slender volume that appeared in the Crescent City in 1900. The compilers are anonymous and there isn’t much on the cookbook’s origins. But there on page 47 is the proof: a pecan pie made with eggs, sugar, “Louisiana syrup,” pecans, butter, vanilla extract, and pecan halves. The cookbook editor noted, “The little lumber town out of Orleans, seems to be the original home of pecan pie. Signs all over Slidell advertise the pecan pie and many New Orleanians drive out to buy them during the season.” The pie uses cane syrup, not Karo, but it’s very close to PPAWKI [pecan pie as we know it]. So. Slidell. Cane syrup. 1900.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-2" id="pp2-ref-2" class="footnote-ref">2</a></sup></p>
            </div>

            <p>There are many reasons to believe that Louisiana was the birthplace of the modern pecan pie and that cane syrup preceded the use of corn syrup. Louisiana was one of the few cane sugar producing places in the United States and numerous popular New Orleans recipes featured the local sugar crop, including the brown sugar in pralines and the cane-syrup molasses in plantation pie.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-3" id="pp2-ref-3" class="footnote-ref">3</a></sup> There are also examples of cane syrup, rather than corn syrup, being used as the base ingredient in pecan pie, although those examples date to later in the twentieth century. An article titled “Best Pie—Pecan—Comes Out of South” that appeared in an Alabama newspaper in the 1950s, for example, implied that the cane sugar pie was the truest version of a Southern pecan pie and provided a recipe.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-4" id="pp2-ref-4" class="footnote-ref">4</a></sup> Yet, I found the story of pecan pie originating in Slidell surprising and decided to do a little more investigating.</p>

            <p>I live in southern Mississippi, about an hour from Slidell, Louisiana, and I’ve stopped, shopped, and explored the city a little over the years. Slidell was founded in the early 1880s when a railroad was built that crossed the Lake Pontchartrain to connect New Orleans to Meridian, Mississippi, and it borders Mississippi. Both Slidell and New Orleans have historically strong cultural and culinary connections to southern Mississippi, so it seemed likely that if neighboring Slidell had become a mecca for pecan pie, Mississippians would have taken note. However, only one recipe for pecan pie made exclusively with cane sugar appears in our community cookbook database and not until 1954.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-5" id="pp2-ref-5" class="footnote-ref">5</a></sup> There are a few rare recipes that use cane syrup alongside corn syrup, such as Amy Brister’s Favorite Pecan Pie from the 1950 <em>Circle Fare</em> cookbook published in Jackson, Mississippi, but in Bruster’s recipe the cane syrup seems to have been added for taste. Her recipe calls for a 1/4 cup of cane syrup and a 1/2 cup of karo. The only contemporary pecan pie in the database, described as a nut pie, is a custard pie from Laurel.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-6" id="pp2-ref-6" class="footnote-ref">6</a></sup></p>

            <div class="chart-container">
              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/county_graph_w_corn_kaor.png" 
                   alt="County Graph Showing Recipes with Corn Syrup" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>In contrast to Slidell’s pecan pie, pralines had quickly made their way from New Orleans to Mississippi and, as previous noted, appear in two early community cookbooks from Laurel and Gulfport in southern Mississippi. Wealthy folks in cities like Laurel traveled through Slidell along the New Orleans and Northeastern Railroad when they visited New Orleans and would seemingly have encountered the rural town’s pie sellers. (There is even a famous story of notoriously poor cook in Laurel who once ordered dinner be brought from New Orleans via train when she was entertaining.) If New Orleans (by way of Slidell) was famous for its pecan and cane sugar pies, why was there no evidence, not even an echo, of that history in Mississippi?</p>

            <p>Equally problematic was that cane syrup manufacturers in New Orleans had not seized upon the Slidell recipe to promote their product. Penick & Ford was founded in Shreveport, Louisiana, but moved to Harvey, just south of New Orleans, where they produced cane syrup molasses under the Brer Rabbit brand name beginning in 1907.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-7" id="pp2-ref-7" class="footnote-ref">7</a></sup> Their syrups were widely marketed as a product of “Old New Orleans” with its “luscious old-plantation flavor of Louisiana cane sugar,” but there is little evidence that they promoted their syrup as useful in the making of pecan pie (although they eventually included a pecan pie in their 1930s promotional cookbook).<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-8" id="pp2-ref-8" class="footnote-ref">8</a></sup> That’s not to say that Brer Rabbit ignored pie makers; they featured a recipe for molasses pie in their advertising as early as 1921 and continued to promote the pie for years.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-9" id="pp2-ref-9" class="footnote-ref">9</a></sup></p>

            <p>A closer look at the editor’s note in <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes</em> raised additional questions. In 1900, when <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes</em> was apparently published, there were fewer than 10,000 automobiles on the road in the United States and no direct roadway between New Orleans and Slidell. There was a railroad bridge, but the Watson-Williams Pontchartrain Bridge, which linked the two Louisiana communities, was not built until 1928. Yet the editor’s note in the “1900” cookbook implied that it was motorists, not train passengers, making the trek to Slidell to purchase its famous pies. “Signs all over Slidell advertise the pecan pie,” the cookbook states, “and many New Orleanians drive out to buy them during the season.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-10" id="pp2-ref-10" class="footnote-ref">10</a></sup> It is possible, of course, that the 1900 copyright referenced a first printing and the cookbook editor added a note to a later edition without updating the copyright, but it seemed unlikely.</p>

            <p>All of this led me to think I needed to take a closer look at <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes Used in the South for More than 200 Years</em>, but before I could locate a copy, I stumbled upon a blog post by Martin Patron, an archivist who works for Cocktail Kingdom, a New York company that manufactures and sells professional barware. The company houses the “largest known collection of antique cocktail books in the world” and their collection includes, according to Patron, numerous copies of <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes Used in the South</em>, but only one with the copyright date 1900. Patron investigated the history of the cookbook and offered some well researched reasons to believe that the copyright date was fabricated to make the cookbook appear older in order to sell it to tourists. Among other anomalies, the cookbook contains a recipe for a side car, a cocktail not invented until the 1920s. As Patron explains:</p>

            <div class="professor-voice">
              <p>Bottom line: this booklet was printed almost assuredly after Prohibition, but no earlier [than] the 1920s. Most likely, it was printed in the 1930s and compiled by George L. Mayer, a New Orleans businessman, for the local souvenir trade. One of the ways we can put this together is [a civil suit from 1939]. That, and the fact we have a pretty good idea whence came the Side car.</p>
              <br>
              <p>We also know that Peerless Printing was involved with early editions of another book, <em>Gourmet’s Guide to New Orleans</em>, that later moved to a different printer. (We have a few later editions of this in the collection, too, but not one printed by Mayer.)</p>
              <br>
              <p>One might conjecture that once Mayer lost the printing gig for Natalie Scott and Caroline Merrick Jones’ book around 1934, he decided to produce his own similar book. And then he decided to lie about when it was published.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-11" id="pp2-ref-11" class="footnote-ref">11</a></sup></p>
            </div>

            <p>While it is possible that George L. Mayer acquired an earlier cookbook published around 1900 and reprinted it for tourists, it was becoming increasingly clear that the recipe for pecan pie and the notes about driving out to buy pecan pies in Slidell were added after 1928.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-12" id="pp2-ref-12" class="footnote-ref">12</a></sup> The cane syrup recipe for pecan pie is just too great an outlier to have come from 1900.</p>

            <p>That does not mean my hunch that Slidell had never been famous for pecan pie was well founded. While Slidell did not establish a national reputation, when I expanded my search to the 1930s, I found a few newspaper references that confirmed Slidell had once been known regionally for its pecan pies. In the early 1930s, the <em>Greenwood Commonwealth</em> in Mississippi provided Greenwood High School an “official page” called “The Bulldog Broadcast.” The page included a gossip column where students poked fun at their teachers and one week it featured this cryptic comment: “And we’ll have you know that Miss Frances Wharton, our dramatic arts teacher, comes from Slidell, La., the town where they use some of their nuts in making the famous pecan pie.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-13" id="pp2-ref-13" class="footnote-ref">13</a></sup> Five years later, a recipe for pecan pie was printed in <em>The Tangipahoa Parish Daily Courier</em> published in Hammond, Louisiana. Mrs. Eva Wilcome, a locally celebrated “culinary artist,” provided her recipe for pecan pie made with 3 eggs, 2-3 cups of white Caro [sic], a tablespoon of dark Caro [sic], 1 cup of sugar, and 1 cup of chopped pecans. This recipe, which is more candy than pie, was described by the newspaper as similar to what was prepared in Slidell. “Those of us who have passed through Slidell and eaten pecan pie as it is served there will be glad to add this recipe of Mrs. Wilcombe’s to our cooking book’s fly leaf. Unlike some pecan pie recipes this one makes up into a more or less caramelized pie as contrasted with the custard pre [sic] preferred by some cooks.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-14" id="pp2-ref-14" class="footnote-ref">14</a></sup></p>

            <p>Neither the editor’s note in <em>A Book of Famous Old New Orleans Recipes</em> nor Mrs. Wilcombe’s recipe claims that the recipe offered is the exact recipe used by the famous pecan makers of Slidell. These recipes, however, do help to clarify the debate about the origins of the modern pecan pie. Slidell, it seems, had a regional reputation for making pecan pies (Hammond is about 50 miles from Slidell and Greenwood is a little over 250 miles), but that reputation was not established until the 1930s. And while Slidell’s pies were sugary and sweet, lending credibility to the idea that they may have included large quantities of cane syrup as Sharpless suggested, since Slidell’s reputation for pecan pie blossomed after the first corn syrup pies and we do not have any recipes from Slidell that pre-date the corn-syrup pie, it is not likely (or, at least, not proven) that Slidell’s pie makers influenced the development of the corn-syrup pie. Ultimately, it is not even possible to know whether Slidell’s famous pies were made with corn syrup, cane syrup, or some combination of corn and cane syrup.</p>

            <p>If the modern pecan pie made with syrup was not invented in Slidell around 1900, then the best clues to its origins might be two recipes from 1925, the first two known recipes for modern pecan pie. Rebecca Sharpless located one in a Dallas community cookbook produced by the Sunday school class at First Baptist Church in Dallas. I have not seen this cookbook, but Sharpless describes the recipe as a “pecan pie made with sugar, flour, eggs, pecans, dark Karo, butter, and vinegar.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-15" id="pp2-ref-15" class="footnote-ref">15</a></sup> It is a recipe that modern chefs would recognize as pecan pie. Moreover, there are considerable reasons to believe that the modern pecan pie was invented in Texas. Texas was one of the largest growers of pecans in the United States and San Antonio was the site of the nation’s largest pecan processing facilities.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-16" id="pp2-ref-16" class="footnote-ref">16</a></sup></p>

            <p>Recipe writers, as we shall see, regularly credited both pecan custard pie and pecan corn-syrup pie to Texas.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-17" id="pp2-ref-17" class="footnote-ref">17</a></sup> In our database, for example, there are three recipes for Texas Pecan Pie, one custard pies and two corn syrup pies, as well as two Texas Pecan Cake recipes. While there is no reason to believe that Mrs. H. W. Woodruff, the woman who submitted the recipe to the First Baptist Church cookbook in 1925, invented the pecan pie with corn syrup, Woodruff’s recipe is one of earliest printed recipes for the new dessert. (Sharpless tried to track down more information on Mrs. Woodruff and believes her first name might have been Margaret, but notes “she has been sadly difficult to track.”)</p>

            <p>Mrs. Woodruff might have been able to claim exclusive title to being the first to submit a corn-syrup pecan pie recipe to a cookbook if it were not for a second recipe, identified by both Rebecca Sharpless and Rossi Anastopoulo. The second recipe’s origins are even murkier than the first, but the recipe was published in 1925 in an advertising cookbook created by Elam G. Hess’ Keystone Pecan Company and the story of the company and its cookbook shed some light on the origins of the modern pecan pie.</p>

            <p>The Keystone Pecan Company, founded in 1912 and located in Manheim, Pennsylvania, was one the many companies that, as Andrew Smith observes (see part one of this essay), “purchased vast acreage in the South, planted paper shell pecans, and sold sections of the plantings as investments.” In the case of Keystone, the company bought land in Georgia, planted twenty pecan trees per acre, and then sold the orchards with the promise that the trees would be maintained, the crop harvested, and the pecans marketed (for a small additional fee). The Pennsylvania company acquired the land for around $25 an acre and sold their orchards for $250 an acre (paid in $10 installments).<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-18" id="pp2-ref-18" class="footnote-ref">18</a></sup></p>

            <p>Keystone aggressively promoted their orchard shares. They employed local agents to sell shares; advertised, especially in small-town Pennsylvania and nearby New York City; courted the press with attention-grabbing events; and, like similar companies, produced a promotional book in 1915 that touted the health benefits of pecans and featured endorsements from the likes of John Harvey Kellogg.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-19" id="pp2-ref-19" class="footnote-ref">19</a></sup> Some time in the early 1920s, the company distinguished itself from its competitors with a recipe book designed to stimulate demand for pecans. No copies of “Fifty Proved Pecan Recipes” have survived, as far as I know, but it was enough of a success that in the spring of 1924 the company ran a contest to gather recipes for a new cookbook. The top prize was $25, and the contest was advertised in the <em>Ladies Home Journal</em> and in newspapers from Washington, D.C., to San Francisco, California.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-20" id="pp2-ref-20" class="footnote-ref">20</a></sup> In response, Keystone claimed to have received 21,155 recipes from 5,083 homemakers.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-21" id="pp2-ref-21" class="footnote-ref">21</a></sup></p>

