                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>To sort through these recipes and to feed their publicity machine, the company launched the Keystone Pecan Research Laboratory in Manheim in October 1924. Hess purchased a meeting hall often used by the boy scouts, fitted it out with a modern kitchen, and hired a dietician and five other women to test and select the recipes.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-22" id="pp2-ref-22" class="footnote-ref">22</a></sup> The laboratory quickly winnowed down the submissions and they were published in spring 1925 in <em>800 Proved Pecan Recipes: Their Place in the Menu</em>. Among the hundreds of recipes, was a recipe for molasses pie submitted by Mrs. Gus O. Selbensen, which is arguably the first (or second) published recipe for modern pecan pie.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-23" id="pp2-ref-23" class="footnote-ref">23</a></sup> Curiously, this molasses pie included no “molasses.” Instead, this very modern recipe called for sugar, butter, eggs, flour, salt, almond extract, white Karo syrup, and 1½ cups of pecans.</p>

            <p>Nothing is known of Mrs. Gus Selbensen and efforts to locate historical records have proved fruitless. Nothing in the cookbook indicates where Selbensen lived and, while the surname Selbensen is extremely rare, I have found no evidence of a Mrs. Gus Selbensen in census or newspaper records. It is possible that the laboratory misspelled the name or simply made up a name for a recipe they wanted to include. The title of the recipe is, ultimately, the only clue to the origins of the recipe and it is somewhat ambiguous. The Selbensen recipe evidentially was derived from a recipe for molasses pie. Molasses, as we generally think of it today, is a by-product of sugar production and was a staple of northeast cooking since the colonial era. Recipes for molasses pie were common in the nineteenth century. However, the term molasses, while not generally used for corn syrup, was also used for cane syrup, especially in the South, so the pie’s lineage remains a bit of a mystery.</p>

            <p>If the Selbensen molasses pie recipe played a critical role in the development of the modern pecan pie, its legacy outlasted the company that circulated it. Keystone’s aggressive sales did not spare it from the effects of the Great Depression, and it was “dissolved into the Keystone Orchard Owners with headquarters in Georgia” in 1933 despite efforts to market their pecans under the Patrician Pecan brand. A quixotic effort to produce a health powder called Pecano made of two-thirds pecans and one-third cashews led to lawsuits, a Food and Drug Administration investigation, and the ultimate end of the Hess enterprises in 1938.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-24" id="pp2-ref-24" class="footnote-ref">24</a></sup> But before the company collapsed, it widely marketed its cookbook (which Andrew Smith calls the “largest compendium of pecan recipes ever assembled”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-25" id="pp2-ref-25" class="footnote-ref">25</a></sup>). Advertisements for the cookbook, which sold for $2.50 and promoted the health benefits of pecans and its company’s pecan orchard shares, were published in newspapers and magazines from Selma, Alabama, to Porland, Oregon.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-26" id="pp2-ref-26" class="footnote-ref">26</a></sup> As a result, the cookbook developed a following among home bakers and food writers. Articles by local chefs endorsed the cookbook in communities as far flung as San Antonio, Texas, and Cleveland, Ohio.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-27" id="pp2-ref-27" class="footnote-ref">27</a></sup>. Yet it is hard to know how influential the cookbook was and impossible to know if anyone who owned the cookbook ever made Selbensen’s poorly-titled molasses pie. Certainly, Keystone did not recognize how revolutionary its pie recipe would become. Although the company featured several recipes for pies in its advertisements for the cookbook, such as a recipe for raisin pie and Thanksgiving recipes for pumpkin and mince pie, they did not feature the molasses pie that was to upend pie history.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-28" id="pp2-ref-28" class="footnote-ref">28</a></sup></p>

            <p>Ultimately, neither Woodruff’s nor Selbensen’s recipe is likely to be the first recipes for a modern pecan pie—they are simply the first printed records that we have discovered—but both represent the importance of Karo corn syrup in the creation of the pie. That is not surprising since Karo products were heavily marketed. Corn syrup, a derivative of cornstarch, did not “crystalize when heated, so it was particularly useful for dessert and candy-making.” It was mass produced in the nineteenth century and originally sold from barrels in grocery stores.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-29" id="pp2-ref-29" class="footnote-ref">29</a></sup> In 1902, the Corn Products Refining Company branded and packaged corn syrup as Karo Corn Syrup. In 1910, as Rossi Anastopoulo writes in her 2022 book, <em>Sweet Land of Liberty: A History of America in 11 Pies</em> (as excerpted in Slate), the company “launched a massive and unprecedented $250,000 publicity campaign to make Karo a household name.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-30" id="pp2-ref-30" class="footnote-ref">30</a></sup> World War I provided an additional boost as sugar rationing encouraged consumers to turn to sweet alternatives. Soon Karo could be found in homes across America and homemakers were finding new ways to use the versatile syrup.</p>

            <p>Cane syrup might have preceded it, but the mass marketing of Karo syrup guaranteed it would eventually become the go-to goo in pecan pie. However, like many new ideas, the invention of the modern pecan pie was probably not an epiphany but an evolution. No one, it seems, was especially pleased with the custard pecan pie of yesteryear and housewives experimented with ways to improve the recipe. In a moment of hubris, I went looking a recipe for corn-syrup pecan pie that predated the 1925 recipes discovered by other historians. I did not find it, but I did stumble across a recipe that demonstrates a critical step in the evolution of pecan pie and suggests, although I can’t prove it, that the modern pecan pie was first eaten in Texas.</p>

            <p>In 1916, Mrs. Weck Mears of Menard, Texas, submitted a recipe for Pecan Custard Pie to a community cookbook that was being assembled by the Ladies Auxiliary of Fredericksburg, Texas. Despite the name and a cup of “cream or rich milk,” the recipe struck me as bearing some similarity to the modern pecan pie. In this recipe two cups of sugar are combined with one cup of water and boiled to a syrup and then butter the “size of an egg” is added. The yolks of 4 eggs, 2 teaspoons of cornstarch, and 1 cup of the milk are then combined and mixed with the sugar syrup. The whole is then boiled again until it is thick and then the pecans and flavors are added. It is later topped with a meringue.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-31" id="pp2-ref-31" class="footnote-ref">31</a></sup></p>

