              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/Weck.jpg" 
                   alt="Mrs. Weck Mears' Pecan Custard Pie Recipe" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>I’m not an expert cook, but I hypothesized that this recipe—sweetened with a sugar syrup and thickened with cornstarch—might produce something more akin a modern corn-syrup pecan pie than a custard pie. A simple custard pie can be made with eggs, milk, sugar, and a flavoring like vanilla or nutmeg. Older recipes often added butter for flavor and a little flour as thickener. The result is a smooth, eggy custard that can be baked in a pie shell and cut into slices. This recipe is different. It starts with a boiled sugar syrup, and then combines that with an egg and milk mixture thickened with cornstarch (which, I will remind readers, is used in the production of corn syrup). The pie is not baked, unless you top it with meringue. Making a custard with sugar syrup was not the norm and making a custard with cornstarch, although not unheard of, was an expedient that was frowned upon. Another cookbook from the same decade described a custard pie made with cornstarch as a “cheap custard pie.”<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-32" id="pp2-ref-32" class="footnote-ref">32</a></sup> Could the combination of sugar syrup and cornstarch, when boiled, produce something similar to corn syrup?</p>

            <p>There was only one way to know for certain and that was to make the pie. My spouse helped. We used half and half for the “rich milk” and Danielle, the former chef, snuck in a pinch of salt when I was not looking. We probably left it on the stovetop a little longer than necessary in an effort to guarantee it was thick enough, but the result, pictured here, was delicious. Despite the store-bought Pillsbury crust, this is the best pecan pie I’ve ever had. I found the sugar syrup a little less cloying than Karo and the milk made it a little bit creamier, but this very sweet, gooey pie is not a custard pie (to my untrained taste buds). It has both the taste and texture of a modern pecan pie made with corn syrup. And you don’t have to take my word for it. An American friend, who lives in Great Britain where corn syrup is not widely available, made the recipe and said that he would never have guessed it was not made with corn syrup. I am sorry I can’t share a slice with you.</p>

            <div class="chart-container">
              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/pie.jpeg" 
                   alt="Modern Recreation of Mrs. Mears' Pie" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>Is this the missing link between pecan custard pie and pecan Karo pie? No, but it is probably one of the many evolutions that eventually produced the modern pecan pie. Perhaps, as the sugar syrup suggests and Rebecca Sharpless thought, it started with cane syrup. Perhaps someone else decided that a simple sugar syrup was easier to secure now that beets were used to make sugar and the price was low. Then someone added flour as a thickener, and someone else decided the recipe was too goopy and substituted cornstarch. These cooks, steeped in the experience that came from making molasses pie, chess pie, plantation pie, sugar pie, vinegar pie, and others, or at least familiar with the techniques used from reading recipes, experimented and innovated and pecan pie slowly evolved. Eventually, Mrs. Weck Mears makes a pie that others compliment, and from there it is only a short hop, skip, and a jump to a pie made with Karo.<sup><a href="#pp2-footnote-33" id="pp2-ref-33" class="footnote-ref">33</a></sup></p>

            <p>Yet, it was not only the recipe for pecan pie that would evolve but also the meaning the pie held for Americans. For more on that story, you will have to read part three.</p>

