        <div class="essay-content" id="pecan-pie-essay-3" hidden>
          <div class="essay-inner">
            <p>The Mississippi Community Cookbook Project’s experimental AI database does not provide much additional insight into the origins of the pecan pie, but it does provide some evidence of the pie’s popularity and the nation’s embrace of this dessert. The number of Pecan Pie recipes in our database alone demonstrates how quickly pecan pie’s popularity rose once custard gave way to corn syrup. Even though the first corn syrup recipes for pecan pie do not appear in our database until 1928—and there were only four recipes published in the 1930s—pecan pie recipes are the most numerous recipes in our digitized collection of over 100 Mississippi cookbooks (around 20,000 recipes) published before 1970. (And it was not just pecan pie that flourished. As James McWilliams observes, the post-Depression, postwar era launched a “pecan-dessert craze” characterized by “diversity and creativity . . . emblematic of a uniquely American way of eating—one that was not bound by strict culinary traditions and was open to virtually any reasonable (or not) form of innovation.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-1" id="pp3-ref-1" class="footnote-ref">1</a></sup>)</p>
            
            <p>The embrace of pecan pie with corn syrup, often specifically identified as Karo syrup, is readily apparent in the recipes that Mississippi cooks shared, although a small but significant number of recipes for the custard variety still appeared in these cookbooks. In some cases, the adoption of Karo was not only reflected in the ingredient lists but also the titles of the recipes (although contrary to Karo’s foodservice website, in our database it was always some version of Karo Pecan Pie and not simply Karo Pie<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-2" id="pp3-ref-2" class="footnote-ref">2</a></sup>). Mrs. E. V. Hirsch called her pie recipe Karo Pecan Pie in the <em>Home Economist Cook Book</em> created in Greenville in 1930. Three others did the same in 1946. Twice in 1947 and once each in 1948 and 1949, Karo appears in the recipe’s title and Karo Pecan Pie was the title chosen an additional twenty-two times in the two decades that followed. But as the number of pecan pie recipes rose, mostly made with corn syrup, the Karo in the name started to feel unnecessary. By the mid-1950s, in fact, Patsey Hailes, the reigning Miss Moselle of Moselle, Mississippi, felt it necessary to call her recipe Pecan Pie without Karo to distinguish it from what was now standard.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-3" id="pp3-ref-3" class="footnote-ref">3</a></sup></p>

            <div class="chart-container">
              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/corn%20vs%20non%20corn.png" 
                   alt="Corn Syrup vs Non-Corn Syrup Chart" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>Recipe titles also provide insight into the perceived, if not the actual, origins of these recipes. Initially when pecan pie was associated with a place, it was often associated with a state and the state with the most probable claim to have been the site of its invention, Texas, was also the most recognized in our database. Texas had a long history with pecans and in the first few decades after pecan production took off in the early twentieth century, Texas dominated the trade.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-4" id="pp3-ref-4" class="footnote-ref">4</a></sup> Although Texas was never as closely linked to pecan pie as Boston was to beans, Maryland to crab, or New Orleans to pralines, it was not uncommon for pecan pie to be referred to as Texas Pecan Pie. M.B.’s recipe published by Sarah Rorer in 1898 in the <em>Ladies Home Journal</em> was titled Texas Pecan Pie and in our database of Mississippi cookbooks, the association was made three times—in 1958, 1964, and 1968.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-5" id="pp3-ref-5" class="footnote-ref">5</a></sup> In the national press, Texas was associated with pecan pies sporadically, but more often than other states.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-6" id="pp3-ref-6" class="footnote-ref">6</a></sup> In 1940, for example, <em>Woman’s Day</em> ran an article on regional specialties titled “Fine American Cooking” and justified Texas’s claim to pecan pie by noting that “Texas produces far more pecans than any other state.” Curiously, <em>Woman’s Day</em>’s editors described the submission by Mrs. James D. Claitor of Galveston, Texas, as a “very unusual recipe for Pecan Pie,” although recipe was for the standard custard pecan pie that everyone would have made only fifteen years earlier.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-7" id="pp3-ref-7" class="footnote-ref">7</a></sup></p>

            <p>Although an article in <em>Town and Country</em> on the lives of elite Texans in 1957 made passing reference to pecan pie being a Texan “specialty,” the association between the Lone Star state and pecan pie waned and seemed destined to fade away until the tragic events of 1963.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-8" id="pp3-ref-8" class="footnote-ref">8</a></sup> The ascendance of Lyndon Baines Johnson, a Texan, to the Presidency (along with Texans’ desire to erase their role in his predecessor’s death by celebrating everything good their state) seems to have briefly revived Texas’ claim to pecan pie. Articles on the President’s diet often referenced “popular Texas dishes” such as pecan pie, and the Karo corporation, hoping to exploit the connection between its product and the new President, launched an advertisement for “VIP Pecan Pie” in 1964. The advertisement was illustrated with a pecan pie in a window that overlooked the Capitol building accompanied by the assertion that “Capitol hostesses are finding [VIP Pecan Pie] delightfully easy to make and deliciously proper to serve.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-9" id="pp3-ref-9" class="footnote-ref">9</a></sup> It was during this revival that two of the three recipes referencing Texas in our database of Mississippi cookbooks were published.</p>

            <p>Before Texas could reassert its title, however, competing claims from states to the east gained a toehold. These new associations had little to do with the specific recipes proffered, as few recipes differed significantly from one to another, but instead were reflections of local pride and journalistic embroidering. On various occasions, Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana, and Virginia were all given credit for the excellence of their pecan pies and an article in <em>The Home Garden</em> in 1953 called “Mrs. Paxton’s Mississippi recipe” for pecan pie “the most popular of all.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-10" id="pp3-ref-10" class="footnote-ref">10</a></sup> However, the most substantial challenge to Texas came from Georgia.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-11" id="pp3-ref-11" class="footnote-ref">11</a></sup> Georgia had developed a vibrant pecan crop and the state’s production often surpassed Texas’ in the 1950s, but the association between pecan pie and Georgia had more to do with tourism than agroforestry.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-12" id="pp3-ref-12" class="footnote-ref">12</a></sup> Increasing numbers of Americans traveled South during the winter, stopping in Virginia, the Carolinas, and Georgia on their way to Florida, and some were journalists who lauded the territory’s mastery of pecan pie. An article on inexpensive driving holidays in the Southeast noted that for five dollars a day you could eat “all kinds of delicious novelties” from “turtle steak (tastes like veal—has no fish taste)” to pecan pie.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-13" id="pp3-ref-13" class="footnote-ref">13</a></sup> These experiences translated into the naming of some recipes as “Georgia” pecan pie. A series of articles about “how young America Eats” in the <em>Ladies Home Journal</em> in the 1950s offered a “southern specialties” menu that ended with a “Georgia Pecan Pie” (although the selected entrée, “baked pork chops with beans,” might leave one questioning the thoroughness of the writers’ research).</p>

            <p>Yet the profusion of new state associations did not dethrone Texas so much as it awarded everyone a blue ribbon, ultimately paving the way for the broad embrace of pecan pie as one of the signature dishes of the South as a whole. In the postwar period, references to particular states decreased and references to the southernness of pecan pie increased (with an ill-defined “Deep South” sometimes granted a slightly larger slice of the pie). Of course, there was every reason to associate pecans and the American South. Pecans were native to the South, cultivated in the South, and consumed in greater volume in the South. Pecans had been eaten by the handful long before pecan pie entered the pantheon of great American pies. But relatively few recipe writers made the connection between pecan pie and the South before the arrival of the corn-syrup pecan pie in 1925. A custard pecan pie recipe from 1916 in <em>Good Housekeeping</em> stated that pecan pie was a “favorite in the South and good in any locality,” but a recipe in the same magazine from six years earlier had made no reference to the South. While it is a little surprising that it took so long for a solid consensus to emerge that pecan pie was Southern despite no one arguing otherwise (unless we count the states seeking exclusive claims), the fact that the modern pecan pie owed its existence to a cup of Karo syrup made in a factory outside Chicago by a company headquartered in New York may have muddied the waters.</p>

            <p>This limited association between pecan pie and the former states of the Confederacy changed slowly in the first couple of decades after pecan pie’s status rose with the introduction of Karo syrup pies.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-14" id="pp3-ref-14" class="footnote-ref">14</a></sup> In part, this may have been a paradoxical response to the national embrace of the dessert. A widely disseminated article on “American Cooking” in 1930 quoted Joseph Wilshire, “who has been identified with the food industry for more than thirty years,” about the emergence of a “a representative American menu fast being adopted in every home.” He claimed that America’s regional dishes had become national and cited Texas Pecan Pie as a prime example.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-15" id="pp3-ref-15" class="footnote-ref">15</a></sup> And as the dessert gained national status, it seems it was increasingly important to highlight its origins in the South. Pecan pie became a dish not only prepared in the South, but a dessert representative of the South.</p>

            <p>Referencing pecan pie’s regional identity became increasingly common in 1940s, gained further traction in the 1950s (encouraged, perhaps, by the arrival of the Connecticut Pie Company’s frozen “Southern pecan pies” in grocery stores), and was nearly mandatory by the 1960s.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-16" id="pp3-ref-16" class="footnote-ref">16</a></sup> Two advertisements from Crisco demonstrate how the southernness of Pecan Pie evolved. In 1935, the company featured a recipe for Sally’s Pecan Perfection Pie (made with both Crisco and corn syrup) without any reference to the South. In 1951, ads featured Crisco’s Plantation Pecan Pie (made using Crisco as a substitute for corn syrup) described the pie as an “Old Deep-South Favorite” that “old-time Dixie cooks won fame with,” now made better with Crisco.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-17" id="pp3-ref-17" class="footnote-ref">17</a></sup></p>

