                   alt="Crisco Plantation Pecan Pie Advertisement" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>The “old-time Dixie” trope was often invoked. A 1940s series called “So Good Meals” in <em>Better Homes and Gardens</em> solicited recipes from across the country. One installment of the series included an image of a Black mammy and observed that recipes from the “Deep South” are “great with memories of generations of family dinners, of faithful dark hands creating tantalizing goodness from simple things.” Pecan pie was not given pride of place among the other “true Southern dishes,” but a recipe was included.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-18" id="pp3-ref-18" class="footnote-ref">18</a></sup> The “Line a Day” column in <em>Ladies’ Home Journal</em> described pecan pie as the “old South at its sunny best” in 1950 and <em>Better Homes and Gardens</em> featured a “luscious pecan pie” in 1953 described as “an old-time favorite of Southern belles and beaux.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-19" id="pp3-ref-19" class="footnote-ref">19</a></sup> (Further emphasizing regional peculiarities, the magazine provided an alternative recipe that reduced the sugar for those not accustomed to pies this “extra rich and sweet.”)</p> 

            <p>Even if articles did not reference Southern belles, moonlight, or magnolias, the association between pecan pie and the South was axiomatic.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-20" id="pp3-ref-20" class="footnote-ref">20</a></sup> An article in <em>Seventeen</em> highlighting regional foods, “As American as Our Map,” credited its recipe for pecan pie to the “deep South.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-21" id="pp3-ref-21" class="footnote-ref">21</a></sup> An article on restaurants in New England explained that the pecan pie featured at the Abner Wheeler house was “borrowed” from “their Southern friends.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-22" id="pp3-ref-22" class="footnote-ref">22</a></sup> And recipes for pecan pie from the <em>Ladies Home Journal</em>, <em>Woman’s Day</em>, and <em>Good Housekeeping</em>, all called their pies “Southern Pecan Pie.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-23" id="pp3-ref-23" class="footnote-ref">23</a></sup> In a strangest twist, a recipe began to circulate for Yankee Pecan Pie, a recipe presumed to be new, that borrowed its culinary logic from the custard pecan pie of the past and could only be called Yankee in the sense that it was not the corn syrup pie now so firmly associated with the South. As an article from Pampa, Texas, of all places, explained, the Yankee Pecan Pie” differs from the southern version in that the filling is a custard-type mixture made with evaporated milk.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-24" id="pp3-ref-24" class="footnote-ref">24</a></sup></p>

            <p>In contrast, in our recipe database, very few contributors opted to describe their recipes as Southern Pecan Pie, perhaps because they thought it unnecessary given that these recipes were printed in Southern community cookbooks, but a few contributors risked overkill and followed the national trend. Mrs. Robert J. Johnson led the way in 1947 with her submission to <em>From Clinton Kitchens</em>, Mrs. H. M. Wise added Southern (and a teaspoon of vanilla) to her recipe in <em>Straight from the Galley</em> in 1952, and Mrs. Zack Buckalew and Mrs. S. S. Allen appended Southern to their recipes in 1954. Mrs. Julia Hewes took it a step further with her Southern Pecan Pie from Georgia submitted to <em>What’s Cookin’</em> in Brookhaven in 1963.</p>

            <p>By the 1960s, there was little ambiguity about the southernness of pecan pie (although, after the Johnsons arrived in the White House, it might also be described as simply Texan). When the <em>Ladies’ Home Journal</em> published a series of articles on regional favorite dishes to promote the publication of a new cookbook, the segment “from The South, Savory Perfection” featured four dishes: Kentucky Chicken, Sally Lunn cake, Ham-and-Sausage Jambalaya, and Southern Pecan Pie (called Southern even in an article on exclusively Southern foods). The rather typical corn-syrup recipe was introduced (along with the other three dishes) as an ageless classic: “Time, tradition and the magic touch of truly magnificent cooks have created the cuisine we relish as Southern and superb.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-25" id="pp3-ref-25" class="footnote-ref">25</a></sup> Nor was the association between pecan pies and the South limited to recipes. Short stories, essays on food, and advice columns nonchalantly linked the South and pecan pie.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-26" id="pp3-ref-26" class="footnote-ref">26</a></sup> A story by Ruth Lyon in <em>Redbook</em> in 1962 titled,”Honey-chile: Why do Perfectly Nice Men Turn into Wolves the Moment They Hear a Girl Say, ‘Y'all’?” described how a young Southern woman is proposition by a fast talking Lothario who proclaims: “Well, well, a Southern belle. What a luscious little piece of pecan pie you are.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-27" id="pp3-ref-27" class="footnote-ref">27</a></sup></p>

            <p>Using the South and nostalgia to sell goods was hardly new.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-28" id="pp3-ref-28" class="footnote-ref">28</a></sup> It was pecan pie that was new and advertisers were eager to invent traditions that would erase any memory of the pre-pecan pie South, create predictable annual sales, and embed the nutty dessert in long-established American rituals. By the 1960s, pecan pie was not only a timeless dessert that everyone was pretty sure grandma made using her grandma’s recipe, but it was fast becoming an essential part of the one of the nation’s most sacred holidays, Thanksgiving.</p>

            <p>Pecans are seasonal and pecan pie was long viewed as a harvest food, but it was not until the corn-syrup pecan pie, simple to prepare and apparently very popular with husbands, that the drumbeat for pecan pie to be considered a holiday staple reached its crescendo.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-29" id="pp3-ref-29" class="footnote-ref">29</a></sup> Efforts to elevate the pie’s standing in the 1920s were limited. In 1920, Libby’s Evaporated Milk featured a recipe for the custardy version of the pie in the New Orleans’ <em>Time-Picayune</em> and promoted it as a Christmas favorite.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-30" id="pp3-ref-30" class="footnote-ref">30</a></sup> Pecans, along with other nuts, were a common holiday treat, and it is probable that pecan pies were served at some Southern Christmas celebrations, but pecan pie was not destined to become a Christmas staple. It was Thanksgiving, the harvest holiday, that emerged as the natural fit, and yet early efforts to associate pecan pie with Thanksgiving also were relatively rare.</p>

            <div class="chart-container">
              <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/City_Bakery.jpg" 
                   alt="City Bakery Pecan Pie Advertisement" 
                   class="analysis-chart">
            </div>

            <p>“Gee! I’ll have to make room for that—Pecan Pie,” exclaims a boy spotting a pecan pie cooling in the kitchen in an advertisement that appeared in Alva, Oklahoma’s <em>Daily Review-Courier</em> in November 1926. The advertisement, placed by City Bakery, announced (in all capital letters) “something new!” and advised hosts that they should “mention to members of family and your guests—before they get started on the Thanksgiving dinner—that there will be a delightful treat coming after the turkey. Tell ‘em to ‘leave belt room’ for a generous cut of pecan pie.” Oklahoma, part of the pecan belt and one of the largest producers of native pecans in the United States, was not new to pecans or pecan pie, but it seems that serving a pecan pie at Thanksgiving was worthy of the label “new” in capital letters.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-31" id="pp3-ref-31" class="footnote-ref">31</a></sup> Central Bakery, however, was ahead of its time. Two years later, the Cherry Blossom Cake Shop in San Antonio, another locus of the pecan industry, advertised Pecan Cream Pie (for 40 cents) along with other “Saturday Specials,” but did not include the pie in the section of the advertisement that provided a “gentle reminder for Thanksgiving.” Instead, it recommended customers place Thanksgiving orders for its signature Cherry Blossom Fruit Cake or one of its home-made mince, pumpkin or cranberry pies.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-32" id="pp3-ref-32" class="footnote-ref">32</a></sup> In fact, in the 1920s, when pecan pie was recommended, it featured because it was not a holiday pie. A 1929 article in the Market Basket section of the <em>Oklahoma News</em> observed that serving mincemeat or pumpkin pie before Thanksgiving might lead to the family becoming jaded and “holiday dinner would not be nearly the harvest festival meal without one of both of the pies on the menu.” To avoid this “culinary sin” and still cater to pie-loving family members, the paper recommended serving pecan pie in the weeks before the holiday.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-33" id="pp3-ref-33" class="footnote-ref">33</a></sup></p>

            <p>Still, the tide was turning, especially in the South. In Waco, Texas, the Spring Valley Club Women offered up their favorite “Christmas and Thanksgiving Recipes” and included Mrs. B. W. Lawson’s pecan pie with corn syrup in 1928.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-34" id="pp3-ref-34" class="footnote-ref">34</a></sup> The Tea Room at Maas Brothers in Tampa served up a special Thanksgiving Turkey dinner for 75 cents that ended with Pecan Pie in 1931, and Davidson’s Cafeteria in Springfield, Missouri, suggested you “bring the whole family” to their Thanksgiving meal and, for an additional ten cents, they could have their fill of “pumpkin pie with whipped cream, mince, and pecan pie.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-35" id="pp3-ref-35" class="footnote-ref">35</a></sup> In 1936, Miss Marie Barkley of the University of Kentucky’s home economist department described “desserts such as fruit cake and pecan pie . . . among the real joys of holidays.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-36" id="pp3-ref-36" class="footnote-ref">36</a></sup> Similarly, a syndicated article that provided advice on how to prepare for Thanksgiving dinner boldly suggested pecan pie as the sole dessert claiming it “makes a perfect Thanksgiving dessert” in 1937.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-37" id="pp3-ref-37" class="footnote-ref">37</a></sup></p>

            <p>Many of the initial efforts to embrace pecan pie at Thanksgiving seemed to come from restaurants (perhaps because pecan pie has a rather long shelf life and could be prepared in advance), but some national publications jumped on the pecan-pie bandwagon in the 1930s. <em>Good Housekeeping</em> told readers that “Pecan Pie makes a perfect Thanksgiving dessert, followed by coffee in the living room.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-38" id="pp3-ref-38" class="footnote-ref">38</a></sup> An article in <em>Parents Magazine</em> recommended two corn syrup foods, Texas Pecan Pie and mashed sweet potatoes glazed with butter and corn syrup, for a Thanksgiving dinner that would appeal to both parents and children.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-39" id="pp3-ref-39" class="footnote-ref">39</a></sup> Yet, while some advertisers proclaimed pecan pie as “a perfect ending after a hearty holiday meal,” pecan pie at Thanksgiving was still not the national norm.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-40" id="pp3-ref-40" class="footnote-ref">40</a></sup> In 1940, Camp Beauregard in Pineville, Louisiana, served 11,000 pounds of Thanksgiving turkey to the 11,000 National Guardsmen from Wisconsin and Michigan who were training at the camp. They also served pie. “Pumpkin pie, no stable in Louisiana, appeared on many company menus, vying with the local delicacy, pecan pie which the majority of the soldiers had never heard about.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-41" id="pp3-ref-41" class="footnote-ref">41</a></sup></p>

            <p>Spurred by government efforts to promote pecans as a healthy, domestic “Victory Food Special” during World War II, pecan production rose and prices dropped resulting in a postwar bounty.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-42" id="pp3-ref-42" class="footnote-ref">42</a></sup> Both food manufacturers and homemakers took notice and a part of the postwar reconstruction of civilian life would be the anointing of pecan pie as a Thanksgiving tradition. The <em>Independence, Missouri, Examiner</em> suggested pecan pie as a good alternative to the more traditional pumpkin pie in 1949.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-43" id="pp3-ref-43" class="footnote-ref">43</a></sup> The <em>Vidette-Messenger</em> of Porter County in Valparaiso, Indiana advised readers “it’s time to bring out . . . pecan pie for a Thanksgiving dessert” the same year.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-44" id="pp3-ref-44" class="footnote-ref">44</a></sup></p>

            <p>If the creation of this new holiday tradition came in fits and starts, pecan pie was nonetheless slowly making inroads (often replacing an older tradition of serving fruit cake). Food writers and advertisers advanced the cause considerably by creating and promoting a hybrid pie, pumpkin and pecan, which began to appear in Thanksgiving menus in the 1930s and gained a widespread following as a Thanksgiving alternative in the 1940s and 1950s.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-45" id="pp3-ref-45" class="footnote-ref">45</a></sup> In 1954, the Madison, Wisconsin <em>Capital Times</em> spoke of the pecan-pumpkin pie in glowing terms: “Sometimes there comes along a dessert which receives such acclaim that you tuck it away in your memory for special occasions. . . . Pumpkin Pecan Pie is in keeping with the festive atmosphere of Thanksgiving Day, too. It follows deliciously the old Thanksgiving dinner tradition of pumpkin pie for dessert.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-46" id="pp3-ref-46" class="footnote-ref">46</a></sup> But in the postwar era, hosts increasingly did not have to make excuses for serving pecan pie at Thanksgiving. An article from Louisville, KY, observed that some families might “have your special dessert for this family and truly American meal, but wherever you go you’ll find pecan pie as well as mincemeat and pumpkin.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-47" id="pp3-ref-47" class="footnote-ref">47</a></sup> Mercedes Wheeler, Food Editor for the <em>Daily Oklahoman</em>, agreed. She felt the Oklahoma tradition of a “rich pecan pie” at Thanksgiving had become a “country-wide favorite” and that mincemeat “probably ranks behind pecan and pumpkin pies.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-48" id="pp3-ref-48" class="footnote-ref">48</a></sup> Mrs. Nash certainly seemed to think that was true when she offered her 20-year old corn-syrup pecan pie recipe to readers of the <em>Santa Barbara News-Press</em> in California for an article in which local women “divulge recipes” they planned to use for the Thanksgiving holiday.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-49" id="pp3-ref-49" class="footnote-ref">49</a></sup> Likewise, 1961 photospread for an article on Thanksgiving gives the pecan pie pride of place on a shelf above the other Thanksgiving staples and the suggested menu offered pecan pie as the only dessert.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-50" id="pp3-ref-50" class="footnote-ref">50</a></sup></p>

            <p>The association between pecan pie and Thanksgiving, along with its celebration as the signature dish of the South, invested the pecan pie with new, cultural meanings. Increasingly, Americans spoke about pecan pie as if it had always been preeminent on the Thanksgiving table. A prize-winning Thanksgiving recipe from a newspaper in Oregon in the mid 1930s, when Karo Pecan Pie was only ten years old, spoke of “creole babies ‘with flashing eyes’ that glow with the prospect of eating a slice of that rich old N’Orleans favorite, karo pecan pie!”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-51" id="pp3-ref-51" class="footnote-ref">51</a></sup> A “Southern Pecan Pie” recipe using corn syrup from the <em>Chicago Tribune</em> a few years later was accompanied by the promise that “this rich, golden pecan pie is an old stand-by with southern cooks, and it’s sure to be a favorite with sweet-toothed families and guests.”<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-52" id="pp3-ref-52" class="footnote-ref">52</a></sup> Unapologetically, Mrs. Bruce R. Ikenberry, Virginia’s representative in the 1959-60 Mrs. America pageant, shared her recipe for a “Colonial Innkeeper’s Pecan Pie” made with corn syrup although neither corn syrup nor pecan pie existed in the colonial era. (Mrs. America contestants were judged on their “homemaking skills,” not their knowledge of history, but Mrs. Virginia did not win the national contest.<sup><a href="#pp3-footnote-53" id="pp3-ref-53" class="footnote-ref">53</a></sup>)</p>

            <p>This sense of history and place helped pecan pie fulfill Thanksgiving’s original promise, made in the run-up to the Civil War, to be a holiday that united the North and South. As part of the Thanksgiving meal, pecan pie (along with sweet potatoes) provided regional balance to a holiday with deep New England roots.</p>

            <h3>Conclusions</h3>
            <p>Bangs are rare; whimpers are common. History happens through small changes as people adapt and innovate. That is the story of pecan pie’s invention and its widespread embrace as a signature Southern dish and a Thanksgiving tradition. We may never know if cane syrup was used before corn syrup or who created the modern pecan pie, and despite the time I have spent combining through cookbooks looking for the “big bang” of pecan pie baking, it probably does not matter.</p>

            <p>I stumbled into this project expecting to write a simple tale about why pecan pie was so popular in Mississippi, but the story that has emerged is much more than I expected. The creation of a new pecan pie made with corn syrup demonstrates the creativity of American homemakers. Pecan pie is simple, but collectively thousands of cooks across decades experimented, revised, and reinvented. They did not wait for Karo and company to tell them what worked; they discovered it themselves. It is easy to get nostalgic about food and to treat grandma’s recipe as sacrosanct, but the more you look deeply into the history of cooking the more you realize that grandma did not think her recipe was perfect. Grandma experimented. And we should too.</p>

            <p>The rise of the pecan pie not only reminds us that our most cherished recipes may not be nearly as old as we imagine but also is a warning that our historical memory plays tricks on us. Collective memory, in this case our belief that pecan pie has always been the centerpiece of every Thanksgiving, is rarely an accurate measure of the past, even if it can reveal a lot about the present. If we are craving a colonial pecan pie, it is not just the sugar we are longing for, but also a sense of being part of a stable, unified nation. In making pecan pie, Americans found a modicum of domestic stability that the Cold War’s threat of nuclear destruction endangered. In incorporating that pie into the national cuisine, Americans found unity at a moment when divisions over civil rights threatened to awaken regional discord.</p>

            <p>I should have seen this coming. My forthcoming book on community cookbooks makes similar arguments about the power of local cooks and the emergence of a national cuisine. But, initially, I missed it. I assumed a pecan pie was just a pecan pie, but our foodways are never that simple. What we eat reflects not only who we are, but who we want to be and in the twentieth century, the corn-syrup laden pecan pie offered Americans a gooey, sugary idyll they needed.</p>

